ells","Organised tubular formations","Papillary architecture","Well-formed glandular structures"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDiffuse-type gastric adenocarcinoma has distinct histological features. \u003Cstrong\u003EInfiltrative signet ring cells\u003C/strong\u003E are the hallmark finding, characterised by cells with abundant intracellular mucin that pushes the nucleus to the periphery, giving them their characteristic \u0027signet ring\u0027 appearance (Image). These cells infiltrate the gastric wall diffusely and individually, rather than forming organized structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn contrast, \u003Cstrong\u003Ewell-formed glandular structures\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eorganised tubular formations\u003C/strong\u003E are typical of intestinal-type gastric adenocarcinoma. \u003Cstrong\u003ECohesive cell clusters\u003C/strong\u003E are not seen in diffuse-type gastric cancer, as these tumours characteristically show loss of E-cadherin expression, leading to reduced cell-cell adhesion. \u003Cstrong\u003EPapillary architecture\u003C/strong\u003E is more commonly associated with intestinal-type gastric adenocarcinoma or other gastrointestinal tract malignancies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diffuse gastric adenocarcinoma is characterised histologically by poorly cohesive signet ring cells that infiltrate the gastric wall diffusely.","Signet ring cells contain abundant intracellular mucin that pushes the nucleus to the periphery of the cell.","Loss of E-cadherin expression is a key molecular feature of diffuse gastric cancer."],"references":["Ajani JA, Lee J, Sano T, Janjigian YY, Fan D, Song S. Gastric adenocarcinoma. Nat Rev Dis Primers. 2017 Jun 1;3:17036. doi: 10.1038/nrdp.2017.36. PMID: 28569272","Menon G, El-Nakeep S, Babiker HM. Gastric Cancer. [Updated 2024 Oct 28]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. 